loopjefe-lv2 (1.3.0-1) trixie; urgency=medium

  * Tempo-follow stretch is now a hand-rolled WSOLA voice (src/wsola.h),
    replacing the Rubber Band R3 render cache. librubberband-dev is no
    longer a build dependency -- tempo-follow ships self-contained. The
    code is derived from SoundTouch's WSOLA (Olli Parviainen) and is
    LGPL-2.1-licensed; the rest of the plugin stays GPL. Source:
    https://www.surina.net/soundtouch/.
  * pkg-config is no longer a build dependency: the bundle Makefiles only
    shell out to `pkg-config --cflags lv2` under MACOS=true (the macOS dev
    path); the Linux/MOD-device build uses the system lv2 headers from
    lv2-dev directly.
  * State machine unification: the engine's 9-state enum (STATE_EMPTY
    through STATE_OVERDUB_CLOSE) is now written directly to the `state`
    output port. The 1.2.0-era 5-value surface wrapper
    (SURFACE_EMPTY/RECORDING/OVERDUB/PLAYBACK/STOPPED) is gone; the
    .ttl scalePoints now expose all 9 states (Record Arm, Record Close,
    Overdub Arm, Overdub Close are visible). The `state` port is a pure
    read-only feedback port -- the engine state is the single source of
    truth for both the LED/UI display and the advance/reset logic.
  * modgui: the hub no longer walks a client-side surface cycle on tap;
    it fires the `advance` input port, and the engine drives the visible
    state from `state` on the next block. The hub's port role is now
    `output-control-port` (the previously-misrouted `input-control-port`
    was a latent bug -- the hub never actually wrote the value; only the
    engine does).
  * MOD Desktop support: new `make mod-desktop` target builds .dylib
    bundles and installs them to ~/Library/Audio/Plug-Ins/LV2, with
    manifest.ttl rewritten to point at the .dylib. tools/resign-mod-desktop.sh
    re-signs a copy of MOD Desktop with
    com.apple.security.cs.disable-library-validation so it will load
    unsigned third-party LV2s (the original /Applications copy is signed
    with library-validation on and is SIP-protected; can't be re-signed
    in place). docs/running-on-mod-desktop.md walks the full workflow.
  * Bundle validation: `make validate` runs `lv2info`/`lv2ls` (lilv)
    against a staged install of both bundles and asserts the port count
    matches what the TTL declares -- catches TTL/manifest breakage and
    C++-enum-vs-.ttl drift that the in-process engine tests can't see.
    lv2_validate is too noisy for MOD-style TTLs (it flags every mod:
    property as undefined) so lilv is what we actually need.
  * New engine tests: test_wsola.cpp (search/OLA correctness across the
    0.5x-2x tempo range, mono+stereo), test_seam_continuity.cpp (the
    anti-click crossfade at the loop wrap -- nothing else exercised this),
    test_bpm_ramp_tracking.cpp (cursor pinning under a continuously
    changing transport tempo -- reseeded from phase01 every block, so it
    doesn't drift regardless of how the BPM ramps), and
    test_overdub_tempo_follow.cpp (overdub layered against a
    tempo-shifted loop, and the recorded_bpm / length invariants).

 -- Cam Gorrie <sastraxi@gmail.com>  Mon, 06 Jul 2026 14:30:00 +0000

loopjefe-lv2 (1.2.0-1) trixie; urgency=medium

  * Tempo-follow: recorded loops now follow the host transport tempo,
    pitch-preserved, via Rubber Band R3 real-time stretching. Change the
    BPM in MOD and existing loops retune to match without changing pitch.
  * New advance/reset footswitch model: the state port is now read-only
    feedback (for the LED / MOD UI); a new momentary advance input steps
    the cycle (Empty -> Recording -> Playback <-> Stopped). reset is
    mode-aware: abort the take while recording, pop the last layer while
    overdubbing (cursor preserved), or wipe everything from other states.
    Overdub is armed from Playback via reset (RC-505 two-button-per-track
    model: shortpress = advance, longpress = reset).
  * Beat-synced record lifecycle: record start quantizes to the next
    downbeat; stop rounds the loop to the nearest whole bar (sub-half-bar
    takes are discarded). Overdub arm/commit quantize to the next loop
    wrap. Free-run fallback when transport is stopped or absent.
  * Tempo-change-mid-capture abort: changing the transport BPM while
    recording or overdubbing drops the in-progress take/layer cleanly
    (Recording -> Empty; Overdub -> Playback, cursor preserved) rather
    than committing a stretched or fractional-length capture.
  * Phase anchoring: loops now stay bar-locked to the transport at
    constant tempo (the old free-running counter drifted ~0.5
    sample/loop against a fractional true bar length). The playback
    cursor re-seeds from time:bar / time:barBeat every block.
  * Overdub layering is pure-additive by default (OVERDUB_DECAY = 1.0,
    matching the RC-505 "ensemble" mode). Repeated overdubs can push past
    0dBFS -- put a limiter after loopjefe if you need level control.
  * Renamed SooperLooper -> LoopJefe throughout (URIs, modgui, brand,
    labels). Jesse Chappell's copyright headers retained (GPL).

 -- Cam Gorrie <sastraxi@gmail.com>  Mon, 06 Jul 2026 00:00:00 +0000

loopjefe-lv2 (1.1.0-1) trixie; urgency=medium

  * Add modgui/ (HTML + CSS) for both bundles so MOD-UI renders a custom
    pedal instead of the generic control-port panel. Hub shows the icon
    for the *next* state on tap (rec dot in Empty, check in Recording,
    stop square in Playback, play triangle in Stopped), with a colored
    ring indicating the *current* state (red/green/white). Undo, Reset,
    and Redo sit below the hub as labelled square buttons.
  * Collapse the surface state cycle to 4 states (Empty -> Recording ->
    Playback <-> Stopped). The one-footswitch UX cannot disambiguate
    "exit overdub" from "start a second overdub" so the surface never
    routes a tap to SURFACE_OVERDUB. The full Overdub engine path
    (STATE_OVERDUB, beginOverdub, per-sample overdub branch) is kept
    in src/shared.h for the day a second footswitch reintroduces it
    on the surface; the SURFACE_OVERDUB case in the state-port switch
    is preserved as a safety-net that bounces back to SURFACE_PLAYBACK.
  * Mode-aware reset: reset while Recording aborts the take and lands
    on Empty (the only state with a transition back to Recording, so a
    single tap re-arms on the next bar boundary); reset while Overdub
    pops the most-recent overdub chunk via undoLoop -- which hands its
    dCurrPos to srcloop so the playback cursor is preserved -- and
    lands on Playback; reset from any other state wipes everything to
    Empty.
  * Fix tap during STATE_TRIG_START: a tap arriving before the bar
    boundary ever fired previously left the engine in STATE_TRIG_START
    while the surface advertised SURFACE_OVERDUB. Now aborts cleanly to
    SURFACE_EMPTY (same shape as reset-during-Recording).
  * Fix undo/redo surface desync: undo and redo previously forced
    pLS->state to STATE_PLAY but left surface_state on whatever it was
    (e.g. SURFACE_OVERDUB), so the next state-port tap walked a stale
    surface. They now also normalize surface_state to SURFACE_PLAYBACK
    (or SURFACE_EMPTY if the chunk list is now drained).
  * Refactor: extract the shared engine (audio loop, state machine,
    LoopChunk, undoLoop, beginOverdub, etc.) into src/shared.h and
    shrink loopjefe/src/loopjefe.cpp and loopjefe-2x2/src/loopjefe.cpp
    down to bundle-specific glue (PLUGIN_URI, port symbol mapping,
    Makefile-difference). Future state-machine or beat-sync fixes now
    land in one place instead of two.
  * Remove dead code: the plugin->recording, plugin->playing, and
    plugin->started member fields (and all writes to them) -- the
    audio loop keys entirely off pLS->state, and these were carried
    over from the original two-port design.

